I think around here, if anybody has enough interest in it, they can get pretty much what they want.
Again, we've got a hardcore group of seagoing people here, probably only half a dozen,
out of a staff of about fifty that go to sea.
And considering my experience both at Woods Hole and Scripps, I think we'd do a lot better as far as getting the kinds of things that we feel we need on the ship.
Well, of course, when I was both of those places, I was in a hierarchy, of course, much lower down, right next to the bottom.
and here I'm halfway up it.
So I feel that I get just about everything I want as far as ship time goes, and I get all the ship time I need.
Again, having been at sea many, many times, I'm a little bit conservative about how I design my programs.
I always, depending on when you start the game and the ship time request thing, we jockey back and forth.
and then you end up with X number of days.
And then I always design a program to fit within it with some slop on either end, having had, you know, experiences with weather and things like this.
And then what we always try to do is fill in the clinks with other people.
Like this coming spring, we'll be going up north again, and there are two primary programs that are going to be serviced.
And we can do that with probably somewhere between nine and eleven people, but we can carry eighteen.
So what we'll do is, well, invite other people along.
They might be students, they might be people from elsewhere, but we always fill the ship up.
I think our programs, when they go to sea, both, well, in all the programs that we've been involved with at both Scripps, Woods Hole, and here, we've always had a full complement.
We've always

design programs where we can accommodate other people mainly because we get something from them and they get something from us but by and large we get pretty much the ship time that we ask for now it's almost as if it were deliberate now you know I'm as an historian I'm you know signing this from just what I've read so I may have misconstrued it feel free to tell me so but it's almost as if it were deliberate on the part of the University of Washington Washington
not to participate in international expeditions of one sort or another.
Is that correct, and is that a good choice to make?
I guess our track record on that has been sort of spotty.
At one point, because we had one of the major programs of IDOE here, but because of personality problems, I think more than anything else, they had a shootout at the O.K.
Corral, and academia
being the conservative sort of awhat word am I looking for?
Anyway, it's sort of the nobility-type structure, and if you're not in the structure, you lose.
And so the group got fed up, and they bailed out and sort of disintegrated.
We do have people here who do participate in international programs, but we're not the lead organization.
Again, that probably has something to do with our backwards outlook on life, and how do you get hired, how do you get promoted, how do you get pay raises?
You know, you just put your body in, and if it always consists of multi-authored papers, then the poor guy's stuck with the comment that he can't do any original thinking.
If he only has single-authored papers, well, then he can't get along with anybody.
So again, with these larger multi-institutional or at least coordinated efforts, the product is almost invariably multi-othered papers.
And for our junior members to get involved with that is suicide.
And a lot of them have gotten involved with it, and they're no longer here.
That's just the way it is.
I think it's kind of wrong.
I think the department chairman or whoever
there's going to be a spokesman at the promotion or pay raise thing, should take the time to figure out what the guy has done.

You know, you can't always tell on paper, but time and time again, we go down and we half-lease things out in our promotion thing, which I guess because of the way we do it, it turns out to be policy, or it can be interpreted to be that, but if the guy isn't
doesn't look on the surface as if he is an individual scientist doing his own thing, he doesn't stand a chance in this department for promotion.

So, you know, you have something like that operating for ten years, and this is approximately how long the present department chairman has been department chairman, he can do a very effective weeding job, and the end result we have has been a direct result of that kind of a policy.
The junior members, the assistant professor level people who
play the big cooperative kinds of ventures don't stand a chance of getting promoted.
And so obviously anybody with any insight or any, or can just notice what's happening around him, if he wants to stay here, he better not play that game.
So that's a big sort of historical thing, and I guess historical can span a decade.
But the other thing that if you look at the hiring and firing record

at this institution up until about the time I came here it looked like they were making it was a definite policy here to fire and not hire seagoing people that's you know that's what the record shows although they keep telling me that's not the case but that's that sure as heck is what the record shows just recently we it seems to me that in order to keep the ship running

know if you want to maintain a facility like that you got to you got to be able to demonstrate utilization i think they they made a concerted effort to swing around the other way so that next year calendar year 78 is the first year in almost a decade where we actually had conflicts of trying to schedule the ship and part of it's due to one of these big programs probes which is something going on in the bering sea

insisted they had to have the ship for 120 days in such a certain window and it couldn't stand much shifting and from a departmental point of view we had to accommodate these people because they're going to use that boat for the next three years so but this county year 78 we sure as heck had a problem and it turns out that our Bruce Frost program and myself
We had to go down to Oregon State and use their boat, which is probably a good thing, again, for political reasons.
We should be more cooperative with our neighbors than we have been in the past.
There's been a change in people down there, and there's been a change in people up here, so maybe we can do that now.
Now, if you were to list what are your major contributions to oceanography thus far, what would you list?
What research are you the proudest of?
Well, okay, I guess I like to think that all the stuff I've been doing for the last decade sort of goes into the food web dynamics.
And I've taken one side of the phytoplankton research.
And the data I've collected, that I've personally collected over the past decade,

comes up with some viewpoint that is rather different than the accepted viewpoint and this has got me into all sorts of interesting discussions sometimes shouting arguments but this probably has been my major contribution is that that I've taken a rather different point of view than an awful lot of people have been taking I sort of goes back to my
my so-called training.
We didn't have really any oceanography, per se, at Cornell, so most of my experience, you might say, has come out of the textbook.
And at that time, almost all the textbook examples came from the North Sea.
And I went out to California.
We started working in the blue waters out there, and nothing fit.
It didn't fit anymore.
And so I've come up with some

rather strange notions in some people's mind about how phytoplankton in the ocean really work the big emphasis has been on physiological aspects and how can you relate physiology to ecology and i don't think that really holds in the ocean the laboratory work has been going on and we've been in the biological oceanography field we've spent an awful lot of money on physiological investigations of
laboratory cultures, but I think by and large they're not really applicable to what goes on in the ocean.

And there is a small group of us that have this point of view, and well obviously I think we're right, but I think we're going to change our attitude on how phytoplankton really work in the ocean in the next decade.
The other thing which
again, is sort of part of this overall food chain thing in the ocean is our work with sediment traps.
And what we're doing is looking at the downward movement of organic matter.
In a period of about 18 months, we've developed a sediment trap system here that's probably as good as anybody else's.
And I like to sort of think that some of these people who've been playing with it for a decade have finally caught up with us.
And I'm kind of proud of that.
It's got me into an area of electronics that I never thought I was ever going to get involved with, having sometimes my doubts whether electricity really exists.
But that's probably the two accomplishments.
One of them is kind of a diffuse thing, which is sort of
goes through a number of papers, and I have a chapter in a book that came out this past year where I finally stood up and said, this is what I think, and this is the reason why.
And the phytoplankton are different than what we've been visualizing them all along.
And the sediment trap work, which is, again, like I said earlier, it's one of the major

unknowns in biological oceanography maybe in the overall scheme of things it really doesn't make much difference but it turned out to be a problem that was nice to work on at that time there was a couple people here who wanted to work on it and it was the right time right place you know right group of people and i think it really worked out quite nicely that was it speaking of electricity uh
Now, is there anything you'd like to add to the tape?
What would you like to tell me?
Gee, I don't know.
You want some biographical background?
I'm going to get that after you say what you'd like to say.
I want biographical background.
Well, I guess one of the questions when we get the student-faculty get-togethers is, you know, you always have to sort of get up and repent and stuff like that.
And I guess in retrospect, I think I made the right choice as far as the profession goes.
It's still exciting.
It's still fun.
I like going to sea.
I haven't experienced any real difficulties in funding and ship time, by and large.
I guess I'm probably about as close as being reasonably satisfied with what I'm doing as you can find anywhere.

you don't know how many of the decisions you made in the past you know were really up for you to make and how you end up how you ended up at this point um I guess you know the old saying is if I had to do it all over again I probably would so I have no real regrets about it we've all well we all when I think of we all I think of my family and and stuff we really have no gripes so
I'm happy with what I'm doing.
You can always think of some better places or some other places you might think would be better.
My experience has been that the quantity of problems are always the same as the quality that differs, and so all in all, I guess I'm quite satisfied with it.
Now, in terms of biographical data, did your family urge you to enter oceanography or not urge you to enter oceanography?
they never thought I was gonna go to college.

So it's uh, well it was kind of, you've probably heard this many times yourself, I was the youngest of four, and being the youngest of four, of course you had a baby, and my brothers are quite a bit older than I am, and when I got out of high school I was digging clams commercially on Long Island,
Heck, I didn't want to go to college.
I was making, actually at that time, which would have been fifty-four, fifty-five, somewhere around there, I was knocking out two or three thousand bucks a month.
And, you know, for a seventeen, eighteen year old kid, that's an awful lot of money.
So, but at, all along, ever since I was, it must have been about ten, I started working, and I've always had, you know, some coins jingling in my pocket.
I like to think I've tried almost everything.
My family was in the confectionery business and used to make ice cream and candy and worked in bakery shops and set pins.
I drove trucks, worked in butcher shops, worked on farms in upstate New York.
And when it was decided, well, it wasn't I didn't decide.
I had a brother that came home from the Korean War.
And I guess I was hanging around with a pretty fast crowd.

he decided I was going to go to college, and we had a little set, too, in the backyard, and I got a black eye and an application to college, and I applied to Cornell to the ag school, and they accepted me, which was really a surprise, because I was just in the upper half of my graduating class in high school, and then, you know, all sorts of crazy things happened.
When I went off to college, I found out they paid people to do this kind of stuff, and as an undergraduate, I worked
for my major professor and ran his field program, ran to Boats primarily, and it's been fun.
So that's sort of a crazy way you get into these things.
Is there anybody with whom you came into contact in your academic career who helped shape your future in particular?
Well, probably the people who sort of pushed me ahead
at both Woods Hole and Scripps.

I never really sat down and hammered out, you might say, scientific ideas with these people, but they almost invariably put me into positions where I could do things that I wanted to do, which wasn't always the general case.
And he said, well, the guy who ran the group down at Scripps, Morris Blackburn, this Australian, who was a funny kind of a guy,

At the time, I didn't fully appreciate him, but he was a heck of a good manager, you know, and he did a lot of things for us that we, the scientists in the group, they could never have done it themselves.
When I went off to Woods Hole, I was with the Reiser group up there, and the opportunities to do things were just all over the place, and all you had to do was do them.
And I don't know whether

know this was done on purpose because the other younger guys in the group I mean we all had the same opportunities and had opportunities to design cruises to areas that we wanted to go to we could you know raise questions and collect data to answer them and so I think I've just been very lucky all along the way to be associated with people who who had good things happen to them that's

one one cruise over I guess one of the things that sort of summarized this up is uh we had a cruise off Africa and there was a kid on the boat I used to get dysentery every time he went three miles from the United States every time he got on the boat he got seasick and I went down we were checking on him to see if he was still alive because we didn't carry doctors in those days and he'd been crawling out of state room to go to the head and the steel door slammed on his hand and he's laying there on the floor
And I woke up to him, and I shake him, and I say, Lou, are you okay?
And he looks up to me, and he says, stick with Lorenzen, and good things will happen.
But, you know, at the time I left Woods Hole to go down to NSF, it was, again, it was a personality problem.
It was a shootout.
I was ticked off.
Everybody, the guys I was having fights with were ticked off.
And in retrospect, it was one of the luckiest things I ever did, was go up to the Science Foundation.
leaving Scripps, going to Woods Hole was, again, one of the luckiest things I've ever did, you know.

And, you know, people ask you how do you describe yourself, you know, as far as various attributes, and one thing is that I guess I come out looking like an extremely good biological opportunist, or an opportunist in a biological sense, and I think I've been able to make the best out of wherever I happen to fall.
You know, the old thing of falling into, you know, a lot becomes smelling like the rose.
And again, I would like to think some of it's luck and some of it has to do with sort of insight.

I'm not willing to say which is which, but I think, you know, all along the way I've been, I've done well, and whether it's I've had anything to do with it or some other external force, I can't knock it.
You know, it just seems to be...
They seem to come out reasonably well.
I can't complain.
